oracle on Solana, price feed accounts, write_authority, and related concepts.\n\nThe search results provide comprehensive information about how Pyth works on Solana:\n\n**Key Findings:**\n\n1. **Price Feed Accounts**: Price feed accounts hold a sequence of prices for a specific price feed ID that always moves forward in time and have a fixed address that programs can depend on.\n\n2. **Write Authority**: The payer is responsible for funding the rent of new price update accounts and to pay the fee for posting an update while the write authority has the ability to update the price update present in an existing price update account.\n\n3. **Account Addresses**: On Solana, each feed has a collection of price feed accounts containing the feed's data, with addresses programmatically derived from the feed id and a shard id, which is simply a 16-bit number.\n\n4. **Two Types of Accounts**: Price updates can be written to a price feed account that holds a sequence of price updates moving forward in time, allowing applications to store the address of a price feed account and read its contents whenever they need a recent price.\n\n5. **Push Feeds**: Updating a price feed is a permissionless operation, and anyone can run this process with the Price Pusher.\n\nThe search results focus primarily on the Pyth Solana Receiver SDK documentation and don't contain specific details about self-referencing PDAs or the particular account structure you mentioned, but they provide the foundational architecture for how price feeds and write authority work in the Pyth system.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_011rr1yfgNLixmd4MBJw5da9","session_id":"846c05db-31a6-42c7-8cfa-8e6a53a70110","uuid":"3e2aa67d-240c-42e3-b7b1-1412fabd01d4"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_notification","task_id":"aaab0d63557b0aa20","tool_use_id":"toolu_011rr1yfgNLixmd4MBJw5da9","status":"completed","output_file":"","summary":"Research Pyth devnet accounts","usage":{"total_tokens":68572,"tool_uses":52,"duration_ms":496852},"uuid":"818352e7-8ba3-406d-a93c-95322839b6cb","session_id":"846c05db-31a6-42c7-8cfa-8e6a53a70110"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011rr1yfgNLixmd4MBJw5da9","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the information needed. Let me compile the comprehensive findings.\n\n---\n\nHere are the complete research findings on Pyth Network's push oracle on Solana devnet:\n\n## 1. BTC/USD Price Feed Account Address on Solana Devnet\n\n**Address: `4cSM2e6rvbGQUFiJbqytoVMi5GgghSMr8LwVrT9VPSPo`**\n\nThis was derived and verified live on devnet. The derivation:\n- **PDA seeds**: `[shard_id_le_u16, feed_id_32_bytes]`\n- **Program**: `pythWSnswVUd12oZpeFP8e9CVaEqJg25g1Vtc2biRsT` (Pyth Push Oracle program)\n- **Shard**: `0` (default sponsored shard -- Pyth Data Association maintains continuous updates on shard 0)\n- **Feed ID**: `e62df6c8b4a85fe1a67db44dc12de5db330f7ac66b72dc658afedf0f4a415b43` (BTC/USD)\n- **Bump**: `254`\n\nThe same address works on both mainnet and devnet because the derivation is deterministic from the same program ID and seeds. The Pyth program IDs are the same across mainnet and devnet.\n\n**Account ownership**: The account is owned by `rec5EKMGg6MxZYaMdyBfgwp4d5rB9T1VQH5pJv5LtFJ` (Pyth Solana Receiver program), NOT the Push Oracle program. The Push Oracle program is used only for PDA derivation, but the Receiver program is the actual owner. This is important for owner checks -- if your on-chain program does an Anchor `Account<'info, PriceUpdateV2>` check, it will validate ownership against the Receiver program (since PriceUpdateV2 is defined in the `pyth-solana-receiver-sdk` crate which declares the Receiver program as owner).\n\n**Confirmed live on devnet**: The account exists, has 134 bytes of data, and was showing a BTC/USD price of ~$74,662 at the time of query (publish_time: 2026-03-17T18:39:53Z).\n\n## 2. PriceUpdateV2 Account Binary Layout\n\n### SDK LEN constant\nFrom the SDK source at `/target_chains/solana/pyth_solana_receiver_sdk/src/price_update.rs`:\n```rust\npub const LEN: usize = 8 + 32 + 2 + 32 + 8 + 8 + 4 + 8 + 8 + 8 + 8 + 8;  // = 134\n```\n\n### Exact byte offsets (verified against live devnet data)\n\n| Offset | Size | Field | Type | Notes |\n|--------|------|-------|------|-------|\n| 0 | 8 | discriminator | `[u8; 8]` | Anchor account discriminator: `22f123639d7ef4cd` |\n| 8 | 32 | write_authority | `Pubkey` | For push feeds, equals the PDA itself (self-referencing) |\n| 40 | 1-2 | verification_level | `enum` | Borsh enum: variant 0 = `Partial { num_signatures: u8 }` (2 bytes), variant 1 = `Full` (1 byte) |\n| **41 or 42** | 32 | price_message.feed_id | `[u8; 32]` | Price feed identifier |\n| +32 | 8 | price_message.price | `i64` | Price as scaled integer |\n| +8 | 8 | price_message.conf | `u64` | Confidence interval |\n| +8 | 4 | price_message.exponent | `i32` | Decimal exponent (e.g., -8) |\n| +4 | 8 | price_message.publish_time | `i64` | Unix timestamp |\n| +8 | 8 | price_message.prev_publish_time | `i64` | Previous publish timestamp |\n| +8 | 8 | price_message.ema_price | `i64` | Exponential moving average price |\n| +8 | 8 | price_message.ema_conf | `u64` | EMA confidence interval |\n| +8 | 8 | posted_slot | `u64` | Solana slot when posted |\n\n**For the `Full` verification level (what push feeds use):**\n\n| Offset | Field |\n|--------|-------|\n| 0-7 | discriminator |\n| 8-39 | write_authority |\n| 40 | verification_level = `1` (Full) |\n| 41-72 | feed_id |\n| 73-80 | price |\n| 81-88 | conf |\n| 89-92 | exponent |\n| 93-100 | publish_time |\n| 101-108 | prev_publish_time |\n| 109-116 | ema_price |\n| 117-124 | ema_conf |\n| 125-132 | posted_slot |\n| 133 | (trailing padding byte -- account allocated at 134 to fit Partial variant) |\n\n**Total account data**: 134 bytes (allocated at `LEN` which accounts for the worst case `Partial` variant at 2 bytes). With `Full` variant, 133 bytes are meaningful + 1 byte trailing slack.\n\n### Key layout note on verification_level (variable-width enum)\nThe `VerificationLevel` enum has variable Borsh encoding:\n- `Partial { num_signatures: u8 }` -- serializes as `[0x00, num_signatures]` = 2 bytes\n- `Full` -- serializes as `[0x01]` = 1 byte\n\nThis means **all subsequent field offsets shift by 1 byte depending on the variant**. The account is always allocated at 134 bytes (the max). Push feeds always use `Full` verification, so in practice offsets are always the `Full` variant offsets listed above.\n\n### Actual price calculation\n`actual_price = price * 10^exponent`. For BTC/USD, exponent is -8, so a `price` of `7466237331000` means `$74,662.37`.\n\n## 3. Program IDs\n\n| Program | Address | Role |\n|---------|---------|------|\n| Pyth Push Oracle | `pythWSnswVUd12oZpeFP8e9CVaEqJg25g1Vtc2biRsT` | PDA derivation for push feed accounts |\n| Pyth Solana Receiver | `rec5EKMGg6MxZYaMdyBfgwp4d5rB9T1VQH5pJv5LtFJ` | Account owner; processes price updates |\n\nBoth are the same on mainnet and devnet.\n\n## 4. Compatibility with Existing Codebase\n\nThe existing `pyth.rs` parser in `/workspaces/rng-utopia/sources/rng-utopia/solana/programs/closecall/src/pyth.rs` is **correct and compatible** with the live devnet push oracle accounts:\n- It skips 8-byte discriminator (correct)\n- It deserializes `PriceUpdateV2Inner` via Borsh with the correct field order: `write_authority`, `verification_level`, `price_message`, `posted_slot`\n- The `PriceFeedMessage` struct matches: `feed_id`, `price`, `conf`, `exponent`, `publish_time`, `prev_publish_time`, `ema_price`, `ema_conf`\n- The `VerificationLevel` enum matches: `Partial { num_signatures: u8 }` and `Full`\n- The feed ID in the test file (`e62df6c8...415b43`) is the correct BTC/USD feed ID\n\nThe mock builder in the test file (`closecall.ts` line 49-106) builds a 133-byte buffer using the `Full` variant, which is correct for testing push oracle behavior.\n\n**One consideration**: The current on-chain program does not check account ownership (it uses `AccountInfo` with a `/// CHECK` comment). For production, you should verify the account owner is `rec5EKMGg6MxZYaMdyBfgwp4d5rB9T1VQH5pJv5LtFJ`.\n\n## 5. Feed ID Reference\n\nThe BTC/USD Pyth feed ID is: `0xe62df6c8b4a85fe1a67db44dc12de5db330f7ac66b72dc658afedf0f4a415b43`\n\nThis is the same across all chains (Solana, EVM, etc.) -- it identifies the price feed, not the on-chain account."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aaab0d63557b0aa20 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 70218\ntool_uses: 52\nduration_ms: 496859</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"846c05db-31a6-42c7-8cfa-8e6a53a70110","uuid":"66028a1c-ecf9-416d-812b-6bc90e6a14f6","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Research Pyth Network's push oracle on Solana devnet. I need to find:\n\n1. The correct BTC/USD price account address on Solana devnet for Pyth's push oracle (PriceUpdateV2 format)\n2. The exact binary layout of PriceUpdateV2 accounts on Solana — specifically the byte offsets for: discriminator, verification_level, price message (price, conf, exponent, publish_time, ema_price, ema_conf), posted_slot\n\nUse these approaches:\n- Check if there's a Pyth SDK or documentation reference in the codebase: search for \"pyth\" in package.json files, any .env files, config files\n- Search the web for \"Pyth Network Solana devnet BTC/USD price account address push oracle\"\n- Search for \"PriceUpdateV2 account layout bytes offset solana\"\n- Check https://docs.pyth.network for push oracle documentation\n- Look at the pyth-solana-receiver-sdk source if possible\n\nThe key question: What is the exact PriceUpdateV2 account binary layout, and what is the BTC/USD price account address on Solana devnet?\n\nReturn all findings.","agentId":"aaab0d63557b0aa20","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have all the information needed. Let me compile the comprehensive findings.\n\n---\n\nHere are the complete research findings on Pyth Network's push oracle on Solana devnet:\n\n## 1. BTC/USD Price Feed Account Address on 